.TH "DOCUMENT.LOCATION" "3JS" "November 25, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Document.location \- Document: location property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The read\-only \f[B]\f[CB]location\f[B]\f[R] property of the
\f[CR]Document\f[R] interface returns a \f[CR]Location\f[R] object,
which contains information about the URL of the document and provides
methods for changing that URL and loading another URL.
.PP
To retrieve just the URL as a string, the read\-only
\f[CR]document.URL\f[R] property can also be used.
.SH VALUE
A \f[CR]Location\f[R] object.
If the current document is not in a browsing context, the returned value
is \f[CR]null\f[R].
.PP
Although the \f[CR]location\f[R] property itself is read\-only in the
sense that you can\(cqt replace the \f[CR]Location\f[R] object, you can
still assign to the \f[CR]location\f[R] property directly, which is
equivalent to assigning to its \f[CR]href\f[R] property.
You can also modify the \f[CR]Location\f[R] object using the
\f[CR]assign()\f[R] and \f[CR]replace()\f[R] methods.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
console.log(document.location);
\f[I]// Prints a Location object to the console\f[R]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
The interface of the returned value, \f[CR]Location\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
A similar information, but attached to the browsing context,
\f[CR]Window.location\f[R]
